benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve account audit logs with history by account id

covered: Valid requests: TC01, TC09, TC12, TC16 verify 200 responses, Content-Type application/json, and that the response is a JSON array of AuditLog objects with required fields present.
Empty response: TC02 verifies account with no audit logs returns 200 and an empty JSON array.
Not-found and input validation: TC03 covers 404 for non-existent accountId; TC04 and TC17 cover invalid/partial accountId formats returning 400.
Authentication: TC05 and TC06 cover missing and expired/invalid tokens (401 responses).
Server and dependency errors: TC07 simulates a DB/unavailable condition (500) and TC13 covers degraded dependency behavior (503 or degraded 200 behavior).
Security: TC10 specifically tests SQL-injection attempt in the path parameter and checks for safe failure and no sensitive exposure.
Unsupported parameters: TC08 verifies that extra/unsupported query parameters are ignored and do not break the response.
Performance & concurrency: TC09 (large audit history) and TC11 (100 concurrent requests) exercise performance and scalability; TC09 also asserts acceptable response time thresholds.
Edge cases: TC14 (leading/trailing whitespace), TC15 (uppercase), and TC16 (max-length UUID) exercise boundary inputs.
Regression/integration focus: TC12 targets a previously fixed bug to ensure mandatory audit-log fields are present; TC13 addresses degraded dependency handling and expected outcomes.
gaps: Pagination: No tests validate paging semantics (page/limit/offset or continuation tokens) or behavior when returning very large result sets — TC09 checks large data but not pagination mechanics.
Caching / conditional GET: No tests check ETag, If-None-Match, Last-Modified, Cache-Control headers or 304 Not Modified behavior.
Rate limiting / throttling responses: TC11 stresses concurrency but there are no tests that assert rate-limit responses (e.g., 429 + Retry-After) or throttling/backoff handling.
Authorization granularity (403): Tests cover authentication failure (401) but there are no tests for authorized-but-forbidden scenarios (403) or token-scope/role-based access.

Schema/type validation: Tests assert presence of required fields but do not validate field data types, formats (ISO8601 timestamps, UUID formats inside nested objects), enum constraints, or nested-object schema.
Standardized error payloads: Error responses are only asserted informally (message presence); there are no assertions against a consistent machine-readable error schema (code, type, details).
Content negotiation / Accept header: No tests for Accept header handling or behavior when a non-JSON Accept is supplied (e.g., 406).
Method restrictions: No negative tests asserting unsupported HTTP methods (POST/PUT/DELETE) return 405 Method Not Allowed.
Observability/logging verification: TC13 mentions the system should log degraded dependency, but there is no explicit test verifying logs/metrics emission.
Additional security edge-cases: Tests do not cover other injection vectors (headers/query), very-long/unicode accountId variations beyond typical UUID edge cases.
recommendations: Add pagination tests (if API supports): create many audit logs and verify page size, next/prev links or continuation tokens, consistency across pages, and behavior at boundaries; if the API intentionally has no pagination, add documentation + performance limits tests.
Add caching/conditional-GET tests: assert presence of ETag/Last-Modified/Cache-Control headers and validate If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since requests return 304 when no change occurred.
Add rate-limiting tests: send request bursts to trigger throttling and verify 429 responses and Retry-After header, and validate client backoff/retry behavior.
Add authorization-scope tests: exercise tokens with insufficient privileges to assert 403 Forbidden and verify error messages do not leak internals.

Add strict schema validation tests: verify field types and formats (UUIDs, ISO8601 timestamps), required vs optional fields, nested object shapes and ordering/consistency of history entries (use JSON Schema or contract tests).
Define and test standardized error payloads: assert a machine-readable error structure for 4xx/5xx responses (code, message, details) instead of loose string matching.
Add content-negotiation tests: validate Accept header handling and behavior when non-json formats are requested (expect 406 or fallback behavior documented).
Add HTTP-method negative tests: ensure POST/PUT/DELETE/ PATCH on this endpoint return 405 Method Not Allowed.
Add observability tests (where feasible): verify degraded dependencies produce expected logs/metrics (or route logs to a test sink) to ensure the system records dependency failures.

Expand security edge-case coverage: test very-long/accountId Unicode/percent-encoded values and additional injection vectors (headers, query parameters) to ensure robust input sanitization and consistent error handling.
